answers.value: I am a professor in Ecology at UC, where my research group studies biodiversity conservation to traditional livelihoods in light of climate change. My husband and I have three wonderful children, and I have found it challenging, but wonderful, to integrate my work and family into a coherent and full life for all of us. I welcome the chance to learn more about others working at the intersections of science, the environment, and inclusion.

answers.value:
Immediately after graduating from medical school, I began a decade-long stint as active duty army medical officers, starting with internship in San Diego. I paused between internship and residency to do an operational medicine tour with the Marines. I spent two years as a flight surgeon, but since I got to my squadron just prior to 9/11, I spent most of that time deployed on aircraft carriers at sea. Since I wasn’t too busy medically with 200 of the healthiest people on the planet, I spent time flying off the ship when we were at sea and celebrating a delayed adolescence when we were in port. I even got in to kite-surfing during that time. It was the best job I will ever have.

I met my now wife, Tina when I moved home to Seattle, just after I returned to the US and left active duty. Our son, Liam, now 8, was born there. We now live in San Diego, where I seem primarily to serve as chief transportation officer for our children. As soon as I drove off the car dealer’s lot in our tan minivan (which the kids think is a classic), I knew that I had officially entered middle age. I still work for the Army as an emergency physician, but now as a civilian. I am enjoying the new challenge of being medical director for a geographically large (but resource remote) EMS prehospital care system.
Overall – I’m happy, blessed, fortunate, and grateful for all of the above. I

answers.value: If you are in the Boston area and are in the tech or non-profit space, I'm always looking to connect.

After Stanford, I thought I would go to law school. I took the LSAT, got recommendations, wrote essays, and completed applications to 5 law schools. The applications were in my bag waiting to be mailed the next day when I went to Boston to visit my girlfriend (now wife), Talia. My car was broken into and among the items stolen was the bag with the applications. I could have recreated the applications, asked the recommenders to re-write, etc, but the deadline was very tight. I decided to take it as a sign that law school wasn't for me.

A few months later, I moved to Boston and married my Stanford girlfriend Talia. We have lived in Boston ever since. My first job was was at a large tech company. When travel became too tough on our family, I co-founded a small tech consulting firm that focuses on bringing tech and management skills to local non profit organizations. At the moment, most of my time is spent working with organizations focused on addressing ransomware attacks.

pictures.caption: My wife Talia in Bali

answers.value: If there is one thing that has remained consistent on my journey, it's my love for cultivating community. Stanford will always hold a special space within my heart for showing me what a life of passion and purpose feels like. I'm driven to create and produce stories about communities of women doing amazing things. Last year I was in Uganda producing a documentary, "Go Girl". If you're a passionate creator passing through, reach out and let's connect for the greater good.
